---
import Article from '../layouts/Article.astro';

const title = 'Funscripts for JAV and JAVR: generate your own with AI — FunGen';
const description =
  'Very few JAV and JAVR releases ship with funscripts. FunGen generates them with AI from fisheye and equirectangular VR AV — and 2D JAV too — right on your own machine.';
const canonicalPath = '/funscripts-for-jav-and-javr';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');

const articleLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'Funscripts for JAV and JAVR: generate your own with AI',
  description,
  inLanguage: 'en',
  mainEntityOfPage: 'https://fungen.app/funscripts-for-jav-and-javr',
  author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'FunGen' },
  publisher: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'FunGen',
    logo: { '@type': 'ImageObject', url: 'https://fungen.app/icon-512.png' },
  },
};
const breadcrumbs = [{ name: 'JAV & JAVR funscripts', path: '/funscripts-for-jav-and-javr' }];
---

<Article
  {title}
  {description}
  heading="Funscripts for JAV & JAVR"
  {canonicalPath}
  {articleLd}
  {breadcrumbs}
>
  <p class="lead">
    <strong>JAV</strong> is Japanese adult video; <strong>JAVR</strong> is its VR branch — and it's
    some of the best material there is for funscripts. JAVR is shot almost entirely in
    <strong>POV framing</strong> with long, rhythmic scenes, which is exactly what a
    <a href={`${base}/vr-funscripts`}>VR funscript</a> tracks best.
    <a href={`${base}/`}>FunGen</a> generates the script for you with AI, so any scene in your
    library can become interactive.
  </p>

  <h2>The catch: almost no JAV ships with a script</h2>
  <p>
    Unlike some Western studios, JAV and JAVR releases very rarely include an official funscript.
    Hunting for community scripts scene by scene is hit-or-miss: a handful of popular titles are
    covered, the rest of a large library isn't, and quality varies wildly. The practical answer is
    to stop searching and <strong>generate your own</strong> — point FunGen at the video and let the
    AI script it.
  </p>

  <h2>How FunGen handles JAVR</h2>
  <p>
    JAVR is technically demanding footage: studios ship <strong>fisheye</strong> projections
    (FISHEYE190 / MKX200-style lenses) as well as <strong>equirectangular</strong>, often at
    <strong>8K</strong>. FunGen's <strong>dedicated VR AI model</strong> detects the layout, unwarps
    it on the GPU, and tracks the POV action, producing a full multi-axis funscript in minutes.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Handles fisheye (FISHEYE190 / MKX200-style) and equirectangular JAVR sources.</li>
    <li>8K-ready decode pipeline, tuned for POV depth and framing.</li>
    <li>Full-length, multi-axis output you can refine on the timeline if you want.</li>
    <li>Batch a whole folder of JAVR scenes overnight.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Playing it in your headset</h2>
  <p>
    Once generated, the script plays like any other funscript. FunGen's built-in streamer plus
    <strong>HereSphere</strong> and <strong>DeoVR</strong> bridges (and XBVR integration) sync it to
    the video in your headset and drive your device — <strong>The Handy</strong>,
    <strong>OSR2 / SR6</strong>, <strong>Autoblow</strong>, or anything on
    <strong>Buttplug.io / Intiface</strong> — with latency compensation so it stays in time.
  </p>

  <h2>2D JAV works too</h2>
  <p>
    Not everything is VR, and that's fine: FunGen also ships a <strong>POV 2D model</strong> for
    flat footage, so classic 2D JAV scenes script just as easily. Same workflow, same multi-axis
    output, same devices.
  </p>

  <h2>Script your JAV library</h2>
  <p>
    Load a scene, run a free 20-second preview to check the tracking, then generate the full video.
    Everything runs locally on your own machine, so your library stays private. See
    <a href={`${base}/generate-funscripts-from-video`}>the full how-to</a> for the step-by-step, or
    <a href={`${base}/#pricing`}>download FunGen</a> and try it on your own collection.
  </p>
</Article>
